|norms[vivarium-process]
  :title Working norms for vivarium — prescriptions, proscriptions, and the feedback valve
  :created 2026-07-11
  :version 0.1.0
  :status living
  :authority binds-until-amended

  ; Instituted 2026-07-11 during the doc reorg, at Joseph's direction: empowering
  ; workflow norms with a method for feedback. Genre precedent:
  ; asf/msc/meta-process-review-2026-07-07/PROCESS-MAP-v0.udon. Kept deliberately
  ; small: a norm that is not real is worse than no norm.

  |meta[self-governance]
    :source-sink participant-feedback

    How this document governs and evolves itself, in three imperatives:
    - Any participant (Joseph, any agent, any future instance) may give feedback
      on any norm, at any time.
    - The valve: append a dated |feedback child under the norm in question (or
      leave a TODO.md entry pointing here). Joseph adjudicates; a norm changes by
      amendment, never by silent drift or quiet non-observance.
    - A norm observed to be routinely violated is a finding about the norm, not
      only about the violators — bring it back through the valve.

  |cluster[doc-taxonomy]
    :name Where documents live, and how they stay honest

    |norm[doc-placement]
      :kind prescription
      Every document has exactly one home, chosen at creation: root = front
      doors (README, CLAUDE) + claim core (core/OUTLINE.md, core/src/ segments —
      sole claim truth, #scope-segment-canon) + the ethics/moratorium unit
      (ASF.md, ETHICS.md) + the three ledgers (LEXICON, ASSUMPTIONS; SUPERSEDED
      lives under .archive/ until re-homed); doc/ = durable thinking substrate
      (ARCHITECTURE; design/ plan/ theory/) — **mine field**: source until
      segmented, then dual-home demote or git mv to .super-archive when
      claim-empty (doc/ is not exempt from graduation); the codified phase
      floor is tabularium/*.ordinum.udon; ref/ = true reference, usually
      consulted not onboarded (may still graduate if fully superseded — not
      proscribed); msc/ = session reflections and spikes (instruments may stay
      live while they convict); audits/ = audit deliverables (pending at top
      level; move to audits/.integrated/ only after verified, adjudicated, and
      integrated); .archive/ = accounted-for retirements that may still hold
      residual mine gold (not tactical current dependency); .super-archive/ =
      fully integrated into core segments and/or superseded by segment truth —
      provenance only; do not re-mine as claim source (any former path;
      see .super-archive/README.md + MANIFEST). A new doc that fits none of
      these is a taxonomy question to raise, not a root file to drop.

    |norm[sunset-freely]
      :kind prescription
      :authority Joseph 2026-07-11 — "a program unwilling to sunset things becomes unable to attempt things"
      Archive generously. The main tree is for current working state; a program
      that keeps its whole reasoning trail and evolution in the main parts
      becomes too difficult to maintain and navigate. Reasoning trails, dated
      reviews, superseded framings, provenance — .archive/ (residual mine),
      .super-archive/ (fully integrated or ice), and git history are their
      proper homes; rewinding for any reason is exactly what they serve.
      Prefer graduating claim-empty doc/ prose rather than letting dual-homes
      accumulate as a second mine.

    |norm[archive-accounting]
      :kind prescription
      The dependency-type rule (Joseph's correction, 2026-07-11): the main tree
      must never depend on .archive/ or .super-archive/ for TACTICAL CURRENT
      needs — never "the algorithm we need is described in .archive/..." — but
      historical, archaeological, provenance, and reasoning-trail pointers are
      proper and encouraged. Before the git mv: verify anything tactically
      load-bearing is accounted for in the main tree, and name where (file +
      section, ideally a segment slug) in the commit message. "Probably covered"
      is not accounted for.
      Graduation: when every load-bearing claim in a sunset file has a segment
      (or is pure ice), git mv to .super-archive/ and log in MANIFEST.md —
      **no path ban** (.archive/, doc/, even ref/ if claim-empty and superseded).
      “Still under path X” means not pealed clean yet, or still the right place
      to consult (typical for ref/ primaries — default lifestyle, not a
      proscription). Residual extract lives wherever it still is until then.
      **Compounding:** each graduated file speeds the next pass — prefer
      low-hanging claim-empty ice when it presents; do not re-read it every cycle.
      **Integration is replacement:** core body = present best. Text retired
      *from core* → history layer (git / DECISIONS / changelog), not a softened
      body twin. .super-archive/ = graduated mine substrate after peals. Not a
      live "claim home" pointer table. OUTLINE is the index.
      **Novel / not-yet-primary:** Working Notes, sketch/exploratory segment, or
      msc/ — not forced primacy, not eternal dual-home "law" in doc/.

    |norm[breadcrumbs]
      :kind prescription
      Breadcrumb pointers in live docs are a matter of taste, and Joseph's
      taste governs: pull them back out where they clutter or dilute the most
      load-bearing concepts; keep only those critical for understanding IN THE
      PRESENT — plus the one-line "the trail exists, here is where" pointer
      when a future agent would otherwise re-derive or re-litigate. Git history
      and .archive/ carry the rest.

    |norm[agentic-verdict-is-flag]
      :kind prescription
      :source .super-archive/from-archive/VIVARIA-DECLARATIVE-FRONTIER.md correction header (2026-07-12)
      Static or agentic audit output is a **fallible flag**, never a keyed store
      citizen and never a verified record by itself. Same-model "assessed" rungs
      are correlated opinion. Ground truth is probe / formal graph / human
      adjudication (#norm-probes-before-claims, #norm-declaration-must-convict).
      Do not narrate an unverified :verdict as if it established kept law.

    |norm[present-tense-bodies]
      :kind prescription
      Current-state documents (ARCHITECTURE as substrate, this file, CLAUDE as
      router) change their bodies; they do not grow by addenda. Claim truth
      changes by editing segments. History lives in git and DECISIONS; retired
      terms live in .archive/SUPERSEDED.md (or LEXICON |carve); open work is
      named as OUTLINE gaps or DECISIONS proposals — not a hand-maintained
      ORIENTATION/TODO state map.

    |norm[ledger-duty]
      :kind prescription
      Touch a constant — touch ASSUMPTIONS.md. Retire a term or doc-section —
      append to SUPERSEDED.md. Settle a term — LEXICON.udon, collision-checked.
      Add or change a nomos — declare it in the nomotheke. These are part of
      the change, not follow-up work.

    |norm[no-top-billing-rot]
      :kind proscription
      An outdated document must not sit above a live one in any reading path.
      If a front door is discovered stale, fixing it joins the current task's
      scope; "someday" is how DESIGN.md ended up outranking the architecture.

  |cluster[documents]
    :name Document formats

    |norm[udon-for-structure]
      :kind prescription
      New documents carrying hybrid prose + skeletal structure that wants
      conformance (norms, process maps, the Ordinum, regulae, declarations) are
      authored in udon (~/src/udon/). Prose-first documents stay markdown.
      Existing markdown migrates opportunistically, when a doc is being reworked
      anyway — never as a sweep.

    |norm[udon-safe-subset]
      :kind prescription
      Until the udon reboot lands its decision valve + udon-cli (fmt/lint),
      author within the verified safe subset (recon 2026-07-11): bracket ids
      unquoted; attributes always before prose/children; raw blocks via
      !:lang: never triple-backtick fences; no @-references; never start a
      prose line with a bare colon; treat temporal-looking bare values as
      unvalidated strings; QUOTE list items containing dots (paths,
      filenames) — bare dotted items hit udon defect #13 (fix pending;
      caught in this very file by the udon steward, 2026-07-11). Validate by
      parse:
      !:sh:
        cd ~/src/udon/core && cargo run --example stdin_parse < FILE.udon

    |norm[udon-filenames]
      :kind prescription
      :authority Joseph 2026-07-11 (relaying the convention to the udon team too)
      Name a structured udon artifact `<name>.<root-element-type>.udon` — the
      root element type IS the schema, so the file self-describes and tools
      filter by it (`ls *.ordinum.udon`). Examples: terrestris.ordinum.udon ·
      terrestris.regula.udon · vivarium.lexicon.udon. The schema segment makes
      per-type subdirectories redundant; keep the tabularium flat. VERSION
      lives in the artifact's `:version` attribute, NOT the filename (git
      versions the file; renaming on every bump would break refs and history)
      — a version-in-filename is minted ONLY when a fork forces two lineages
      to coexist. (`.udon` vs `.udn` for the base suffix is the udon team's
      open call; stay on `.udon`, what the parser uses today.)

  |cluster[code-epistemics]
    :name Code-side truth disciplines (the mechanical ones)

    |norm[determinism-proscriptions]
      :kind proscription
      In world-law code: no wall-clock (SystemTime/Instant::now), no OS entropy
      or shared RNG (thread_rng and kin — all randomness is a keyed hash), no
      HashMap/HashSet iteration order reaching canonical bytes or store roots.
      The clippy disallowed-lists that mechanize this are queued in
      doc/toolchain.md; the norm binds now, ahead of the tooling.

    |norm[probes-first]
      :kind prescription
      A known issue gets its probe written first; then the physics is fixed
      until the probe passes. A declared epistemic tier is a falsifiable claim
      and the probe is what would convict it. No physics claim without its
      probe run.

    |norm[land-vs-count]
      :kind prescription
      Every small-flux-into-large-f32 site explicitly chooses: land (compensated
      summation) or count (realized-delta accounting). Conservation test
      tolerances are absolute, never relative. (Paid for twice, 2026-07-04.)

  |cluster[workflow]
    :name Session workflow

    |norm[commit-cadence]
      :kind prescription
      :authority Joseph 2026-07-11 — "commit whenever you see fit, as often as you see fit"
      Commit in logical waves with messages written for the archaeologist —
      future readers reconstruct intent from messages, so say what moved, why,
      and where the accounting lives. Moves are git mv so lineage survives.

    |norm[full-output]
      :kind proscription
      :authority Joseph 2026-07-09
      Never filter a long-running process's live output at launch (no
      pipe-to-tail). Capture the full log; filter at read time. The pipe saves
      lines on success and destroys diagnosis on failure.

    |norm[peer-delegation]
      :kind prescription
      Agents receive context — decisions made, constraints discovered, what the
      work is for — not prescriptions of method. Action-space is not
      deliberation-space.

    |norm[flagged-file-routing]
      :kind prescription
      :files ["ref/research/est-tiw-dossier.md" ".super-archive/from-archive/universal-biological-rhythms.md"]  ; quoted: bare items with dots hit udon defect #13 (fix pending)
      Two reference files trip the current Fable model-family safeguard
      (verified 2026-07-10 twice, again 2026-07-11). REFINEMENT (Fable-agent
      test, 2026-07-11): the safeguard fires on Fable *generation about* this
      content, NOT on reading it — a Fable agent read the whole biology-dense
      ordinum cleanly, then tripped while writing its own summary. So the rule
      is narrower than "don't open": READING is fine; what routes through an
      Opus agent is CONTENT-EDITING/SUMMARIZING of the biology-dense material
      (and any operation that emits it), under a report-paths-not-content
      contract (the agent reports old/new path strings and line counts, never
      quotes surroundings). Path-only ops (git mv, excluded greps) are always
      safe. The engineering distillation a Fable session needs is in
      LEXICON.udon section 8, safe. Extend this list if another file starts
      tripping; retire entries when the safeguard stops firing.

    |norm[whim-gate]
      :kind prescription
      Adding a target-aged world feature goes through the requisite-closure
      check: what does the regula then demand (which slots, which permits
      voided)? Until regula.rs lands, run the check by hand against
      doc/plan/regula-conformance-design.md section 3. This norm is the reason
      the regula layer exists — structure where vigilance kept failing.
